post_text: We are SO excited to be opening our doors once again for students tomorrow morning! 174 days was far too long! Reminder - if you are dropping off your child in the morning, both buildings will be unlocked between 7:50 and 8:00. Please do not arrive prior to 7:50 to ensure safe traffic patterns. If picking your child up, please arrive between 2:20-2:25 for UPK students and 2:25-2:35 for all other Primary students. Pickup time is 2:50-3:00 for Intermediate/Secondary students. See below for a map of both buildings.

Due to Labor Day, the first week of school does not have a virtual day on Wednesday.
PreK-6th grade students attend in-person all four days. For 7th-12th grade students, the Monday/Tuesday group will be attending Tuesday, September 8th, AND Wednesday, September 9th. The Thursday/Friday group will be attending September 10th and 11th.

post_text:
Dear Community,

I must apologize for my inadvertent oversight in not posting to our Facebook page about the community informational meetings. I posted it to our webpage and in my haste to meet the Governor’s timeline for having three meetings within a ten-day period, along with all of the other challenges we are working to meet with all of the mandates, I simply forgot to push the dates and times to Facebook. I was informed by one of the attendees at yesterday’s morning meeting that I had overlooked this communication avenue.

I will be hosting an additional meeting on Monday, August 17th in the auditorium at 6:00 p.m. for anyone who couldn’t make yesterday’s meetings or may not be able to attend the meeting on Monday at 10:00 a.m.

post_text:
Dear Keshequa Family,

Our reopening plan has been completed and is posted on our website. Please remember that it is a living document and subject to change as districts across the state receive new guidelines from state and federal agencies. KCS will update the plan as needed to comply with all future regulations and we will communicate with the community regularly in the coming months. I would like to thank everyone for their patience in these uncertain and turbulent times.

I would like to express my gratitude to the individuals who were part of the Stakeholder Committee for their time, effort, and invaluable contributions to this document. I would also like to thank the KCS administration team for their tremendous and tireless efforts to accomplish this monumental task.

Together we will meet and overcome all challenges and we will provide the best possible education we can for the students of Keshequa.

Respectfully yours,

Thomas K. Kopp
Go Indians!

post_text:
Tyto Online, a subsidiary of Immersed Games, "...is planning a free two-week virtual summer camp for middle + high schoolers to develop students' STEM knowledge and skills as they use science video game Tyto Online to do activities such as suggesting how to solve a food shortage. They will also talk directly with the game developers, learning about STEM careers in gaming, and give feedback on new content and features."

Students interested in participating may indicate that here: https://www.tytoonline.com/summercamp/. They need to reach a target number in order to run the program, once they reach that, they will share the enrollment information. In the "learned about this" segment of the interest enrollment, students should indicate the "Livingston County Schools" portion of the dropdown.
If you would like to enroll but need your Chromebook to participate, please call the school at ext 2017.

post_text: Four $1,000 Scholarships are now available through the Livingston County Area Chamber of Commerce and the Livingston County Education Alliance (LCEA) for graduating seniors living in Livingston County. At least two are typically awarded to vocational (CTE) students. All entries must be received by Monday, July 27, 2020. The application paperwork, guidelines, and directions for submission are available at https://www.livingstoncountychamber.com/lcea-scholarship.

THELCN.COM
Amid pandemic, Keshequa teachers, staff spring into action

Livingston County News
March 20 at 9:30 AM ·

While some districts have opted to set up meal pick-up locations throughout their districts, teachers, staff and administrators at Keshequa wanted to keep some sense of normalcy by maintaining face-to-fact connections with their students. “Our families rely on us to educate their children but schools play a much larger role in students day - providing a warm, safe building and a couple of well-balanced meals.” said Superintendent Tom Kopp. “When the team came together, this work was prioritized to make sure that we had a plan that was sustainable, supportive of our families needs and kept us connected to our families.”

post_text: This month, students at the Primary Building are focusing on what it means to showcase responsibility. Simply put, being responsible means following through with expectations placed on you. You may be given a responsibility (task) but may also be held responsible for your actions. Although it is not always easy or 'popular' to showcase responsibility, recognizing that there are others depending on you is important. Students are also participating in a shared reading experience that will have all students hearing the same book with a theme of responsibility. As a way to support this initiative at home, a 'read aloud' of the same text our students are reading in school is shared below. Feel free to watch with your child and talk about ways in which the characters are showcasing responsibility as well as some real-life examples from home. Enjoy "Even Superheroes Make Mistakes".

post_text: This month, students at the Primary Building are focusing on what it means to showcase integrity. Simply put, integrity means doing the right thing even when no one is watching. Integrity takes bravery and courage and that has been a focus of our discussions on the morning announcements. Although it is not always easy or 'popular', doing the right thing is best. Students are also participating in a shared reading experience that will have all students hearing the same book with a theme of integrity. As a way to support this initiative at home, a 'read aloud' of the same text our students are reading in school is shared below. Feel free to watch with your child and talk about ways in which the characters are showcasing integrity as well as some real-life examples from home. Enjoy "Princess K.I.M. and the Lie That Grew."

post_text: For the month of January, students in the Primary Building showcased the PBIS habit 'perseverance' but participating in the "Principal's Perseverance Challenge". Each day classes were given challenges that focused on mindfulness, fitness, and academic tasks. Each time a class completed the challenge, they earned a Kesh Coin. As a building, students set a goal to reach 500 Kesh Coins by the end of the month. Although the challenges were difficult, students worked together and persevered to meet (and surpass) their goal. To celebrate their accomplishments, Mr. VanEpps had to persevere through the entire Student of the Month Assembly while being taped to a cafeteria table.

post_text: When Science meets Social Studies: 7th graders have been learning about all of the taxes the King of England imposed on the colonists to pay for the French and Indian War. As part of a review lesson. students were given one of the taxes and were responsible for explaining it to the class. During the explanations, different food coloring was added to vinegar as each tax was discussed. The vinegar turned black and you could not see through it. This represented how the colonists were feeling and how their anger was increasing. When the last tax was presented, baking soda was added to the mix! The ensuing eruption represented the start of the American Revolution! The kids loved this hands-on lesson!

During the explanations, different food coloring was added to vinegar as each tax was discussed. The vinegar turned black and you could not see through it. This represented how the colonists were feeling and how their anger was increasing. When the last tax was presented, baking soda was added to the mix! The ensuing eruption represented the start of the American Revolution! The kids loved this hands-on lesson!

This year Keshequa had 5 students chosen to sing in the 2019 Junior High Area All State Chorus. Students perform a NYSSMA solo in the spring and then have the grades received sent in for consideration. Studying, practicing & performing a NYSSMA Solo is a lot of work, as is practicing & performing in a chorus made up of the best students from the Southern Tier.

Keshequa also had 3 students chosen to sing in the 2019 SHAAS chorus. Students perform a NYSSMA solo in the spring and then have the grades received sent in for consideration. post_text: Congratulations to Alicia Cartwright, Graham Howe, Greg Loper, Ally Swain and Lenny Carroll for outstanding participation in New York State's YMCA Model Youth Legislature in Albany. These 5 students gathered with hundreds of their peers from across the state to present and debate bills and learn about New York's government. All students did well, and Keshequa earned some great honors. The bill they wrote and presented earned an Outstanding Bill award, Greg Loper earned an Outstanding Debater award, and Graham Howe earned an Outstanding Delegate award. Congrats to all students on a fantastic conference!

This week we have used hip hop dance videos, Zumba for kids, and even Max Out Strength. Our students are learning about all the resources and options they have to improve their personal fitness any time and any location, even in your living room with these videos. We are hoping they will encourage all our family members to get fit!

post_text: The 7th-grade team went to Camp Stella Maris on Tuesday, October 8th. It was a beautiful day to experience team-building activities of zip lining, the high ropes course and a variety of team building games. In addition to the 7th-grade students, teachers and Mrs. Bennett, 20 Link Leaders attended. Link Leaders are high school students who have been trained to work with the incoming 7th graders in a variety of situations. These students participated and cheered on the 7th graders as they attempted each of the events. Part of the cost of this field trip was sponsored by the newly formed Keshequa PTSA. The next day, 7th graders shared they were sore from the activities, but wanted to know when they could go again. A successful day for our newest members of the secondary building.

post_text: KPS Open House is this Thursday, October 10, from 5:30-6:30. We are looking forward to opening our doors to families and showcasing all of the hard work our students have put forth this year. Make sure you stop in the cafeteria to meet with several community groups, pick up an enrollment form for the YMCA afterschool program, and shop at the Scholastic Book Fair. We hope to see you there!

post_text: On Monday, September 30 students in the Primary building celebrated their first PBIS celebration of the year! Classes teamed up to participate in “Tribe Time” which had them working together to construct the most successful paper airplane before coming together as a building to cheer on teachers, classmates, and our “Student of the Month” recipients. 12 students were chosen by their teachers for highlighting what it means to be ‘safe’ throughout the month of September. These 12 students received a certificate at the assembly and were treated to a special “Breakfast of Champions”.
